<TITLE> Sri Lanka allows Tamil aid ship to dock, says India </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Thu Jun 25, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Sri Lanka will allow a ship carrying aid for thousands of war-displaced Tamils to dock, India's foreign minister said on Thursday, ending a standoff at sea over a cargo initially suspected of hiding weapons. The Syrian-flagged Captain Ali was carrying 884 tonnes of relief supplies for Tamils displaced by the country's 25-year war when it was intercepted on June 4 by the Sri Lankan navy. The aid cargo, paid for by expatriate Tamils, raised suspicion in Colombo because rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) have a long history of using humanitarian groups as fundraising fronts. While the ship floated in the Indian Ocean, Sri Lanka's giant neighbours India intervened, urging Colombo to allow the cargo of food and medicines. Sri Lankan Tamils have historical and cultural links with about 60 million Tamils in the southern Indian state of Tamil Nadu and their fate has political repercussions in India. "The Sri Lankan delegation kindly agreed to our suggestion and these would now be routed to Sri Lanka through the Indian Red Cross," Foreign Minister S.M. Krishna said. The government declared victory over LTTE in May, ending one of Asia's longest conflicts. Nearly 300,000 people, mostly Tamils, were uprooted from their homes during the last phase of the fighting and are being held in government-run c
